Shared Facilities Agreement Between Big Savage, LLC and Mason Dixon Wind, LLC SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT THIS SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT (this “Agreement”), is entered into as of October 13, 2017 (the “Effective Date”), by and between Big Savage, LLC, a Pennsylvania limited liability company (“Big Savage”) and Mason Dixon Wind, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company (“Mason Dixon”, and together with Big Savage, the “Parties” and each a “Party”). RECITALS WHEREAS, Big Savage currently owns and operates an existing wind energy generation facility with a nameplate capacity of 139.4 megawatts (“MW”) (net) located in Somerset County, Pennsylvania (the “Big Savage Project”); WHEREAS, Mason Dixon is developing and will own and operate a wind energy generation facility with a nameplate capacity of approximately 80 MW (the “Mason Dixon Project”, together with the Big Savage Project, the “Projects” and each a “Project”); WHEREAS, the Mason Dixon Project will be located adjacent to the Big Savage Project and the Projects anticipate sharing, among other things, the operation of certain common electric facilities that are necessary to deliver each Project’s electric generation output to market; WHEREAS, Big Savage entered into a certain Interconnection Service Agreement by and among itself, PJM Interconnection LLC (“PJM”) and The Potomac Edison Company, dated as of September 13, 2017, (the “Big Savage ISA”), which supersedes the conforming Interconnection Service Agreement among PJM, Big Savage and The Potomac Edison Company, PJM Queue #U2-073/Z2-013, effective January 13,2015, and designated as First Revised Service Agreement No. 3349. WHEREAS, the Big Savage ISA provides for Interconnection Service (as defined in the Big Savage ISA) for wind generating facilities with an aggregate Maximum Facility Output of 139.4 MWs associated with PJM Queue Positions #U2-073/Z2-013 and anew Queue Position AB2-038; WHEREAS, Big Savage owns a 138kV radial electric line and certain other personal property, fixtures, equipment, land and contract rights, and/or facilities (including the Customer Interconnection Facilities, as defined and identified in Appendix 1 to the Big Savage ISA), which are specifically described in Exhibit A attached hereto that are necessary to interconnect the Projects to the electric system of PJM and/or efficiently operate and maintain the Projects (the “Shared Facilities”); WHEREAS, Mason Dixon entered into a certain Interconnection Service Agreement by and among itself, PJM Interconnection LLC (“PJM”) and The Potomac Edison Company, dated as of September 13, 2017, (the “Mason Dixon ISA”) associated with Queue Positions U2-073/Z2-013/AB2-038; WHEREAS, Big Savage and Mason Dixon are entering into this Shared Facilities Agreement (a) to confirm Big Savage’s obligation to act as the Manager of the Shared Facilities as specified further herein; (b) to allow Big Savage and Mason Dixon to use the Shared Facilities; and (c) to enable Big Savage and Mason Dixon to inject the energy output of their respective Projects into the electric system of PJM; NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the premises and of the mutual covenants and agreements contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties hereby agree as follows: 1. TERM; EARLY TERMINATION 1.1 Term. The term of this Agreement shall commence on the Effective Date and shall continue in effect until terminated (a) by mutual agreement of the Parties, or (b)pursuant to Section 1.2 of this Agreement (“Term”). 1.2 Early Termination. This Agreement shall automatically terminate, without further action by either Party and without further liability of any Party to any other Party (except for obligations accruing prior to the termination), upon (i) the date that both Big Savage and Mason Dixon, or their successors and assigns, shall have permanently ceased operation of the Projects for the production of electric energy, (ii) if Mason Dixon exercises its buyout option specified in Section 7.3; or (iii) if either Party permanently ceases to operate its respective Project and no successor agreement is executed in accordance with the terms of Section 4.3. 2. GRANT OF SHARED FACILITIES RIGHTS 1.1 Grant. During the Term of this Agreement, Big Savage hereby grants to Mason Dixon, on the terms and subject to the conditions hereof, the non-exclusive right to access and utilize, along with Big Savage, the Shared Facilities as may be reasonably necessary in connection with the Interconnection Service received by Mason Dixon from PJM, and as necessary for the efficient ownership, operation and maintenance of the Mason Dixon Project. Big Savage and Mason Dixon shall timely negotiate and execute such other documents as may be reasonably necessary to provide Mason Dixon non-exclusive rights to access and utilize the Shared Facilities as required by and in accordance with the terms hereof. 1.2 Essential Nature of Shared Facilities. Big Savage hereby acknowledges that the right of Mason Dixon to access and utilize the Shared Facilities is essential to the delivery of electric energy from Mason Dixon to the electric system of PJM and that access and utilization in accordance with this Agreement are being relied upon by Mason Dixon, its investors and Financing Parties. 1.3 Vesting. The right to access and utilize the Shared Facilities granted hereunder by Big Savage to Mason Dixon shall be a license and shall vest in Mason Dixon as a licensee hereunder without any transfer of title, leasehold or other interest or rights in the Shared Facilities. 1.4 License Fee. In consideration of the right to access and utilize the Shared Facilities, Mason Dixon agrees to pay to Big Savage an annual license fee of Twenty-Five Thousand Dollars ($25,000.00) (the “License Fee”), payable on the day the Mason Dixon Project achieves commercial operation (“Commercial Operation Date”) and each anniversary thereof. 3. NATURE OF SHARED FACILITIES RIGHTS 2.1 Nature of Services. During the Term and in accordance with this Agreement, Big Savage shall provide certain services to Mason Dixon, including those services Big Savage receives through the Big Savage ISA, as necessary to enable (a) the efficient operation and maintenance of the Mason Dixon Project and (b) the energy generated by the Mason Dixon Project to reach the electric system of PJM. The Parties acknowledge that the grant of rights under this Agreement by Big Savage to Mason Dixon is made for the purpose of enabling efficient operation and maintenance of the Mason Dixon Project and the energy from the Mason Dixon Project to reach the system of PJM via the Point of Interconnection as defined in the Big Savage ISA. For the avoidance of doubt, the grant of rights under this Agreement by Big Savage to Mason Dixon shall not relieve Big Savage of its obligations under the Big Savage ISA or Mason Dixon of its duties and obligations under the Mason Dixon ISA. 2.2 Obligations of Big Savage. Big Savage shall exercise its rights and perform its obligations under this Agreement in a manner consistent with its obligations under the Big Savage ISA. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, during the Term of this Agreement, Big Savage shall: (i) perform its obligations under this Agreement and the Big Savage ISA and otherwise operate the Big Savage Project in accordance with Good Utility Practice, Applicable Laws and Regulations and Applicable Standards, in each case as defined in the Big Savage ISA, and in a manner consistent with the terms of the Big Savage ISA; (ii) comply with all provisions of the Big Savage ISA including, but not limited to, all insurance requirements, payments due, operational limits, operating guides, operating procedures and reliability standards and requirements applicable by virtue thereof; (iii) promptly provide to Mason Dixon any notices it receives under the Big ISA from any of the parties thereto, including any notices regarding Emergency Condition(s) thereunder; (iv) not take any action or induce any third party to act or refrain from acting, without Mason Dixon’s written consent, to terminate the Big Savage ISA; (v) perform necessary maintenance on the Shared Facilities, as agreed to in this Agreement; (vi) ensure that, to the maximum extent practicable, any actions by Big Savage that may, or do, cause Big Savage to fail to comply with the Big Savage ISA, do not affect the service received by Mason Dixon hereunder; and (vii) use all commercially reasonable efforts to promptly resolve any technical issues arising in connection with the operation of the Big Savage Project that might reasonably be expected to result in a default under the Big Savage ISA or otherwise limit the ability of Mason Dixon to deliver the electric output of the Mason Dixon Project through the Shared Facilities to the Point of Interconnection as defined in the Big Savage ISA. 2.3 Obligations of Mason Dixon. Mason Dixon shall exercise its rights and perform its obligations under this Agreement in a manner that is reasonable and facilitates Big Savage’s performance under, and compliance with, the Big Savage ISA. Without limiting the generality of the foregoing, during the Term of this Agreement, Mason Dixon shall: (i) perform its obligations under this Agreement and the Mason Dixon ISA and operate the Mason Dixon Project in accordance with Good Utility Practice, Applicable Laws and Regulations and Applicable Standards, in each case as defined in the Mason Dixon ISA, and in a manner consistent with the terms of the Mason Dixon ISA; (ii) facilitate Big Savage’s compliance with all provisions of the Big Savage ISA (including, without limitation, all insurance requirements, operational limits, operating guides, operating procedures and standards and requirements applicable by virtue thereof) as related to the Mason Dixon Project; (iii) not take any action, refrain from taking any action, or induce any third party to take or refrain from taking action which would result in a breach of the Big Savage ISA by Big Savage; (iv) use all commercially reasonable efforts to promptly resolve any technical issues arising in connection with the operation of the Mason Dixon Project that might reasonably be expected to result in a default under the Big Savage ISA and/or the Mason Dixon ISA, and if such default occurs, to promptly assist Big Savage to cure such default in accordance with the terms of the Big Savage ISA and, if the default is under the Mason Dixon ISA, take such commercially reasonable and timely action to cure such default under the Mason Dixon ISA; (v) comply with all reasonable instructions, as may be communicated to it by Big Savage, in order to ensure compliance with the provisions of the Big Savage ISA with respect to the Mason Dixon Project and the Mason Dixon ISA; (vi) provide Big Savage with all reasonable information regarding the operation and condition of the Mason Dixon Project required for Big Savage to maintain compliance with the terms and conditions of the Big Savage ISA; and (vii) provide promptly to Big Savage copies of all notices and instructions received by it that affect Big Savage’s performance under the Big Savage ISA. 2.4 Rights in the Event of a Notice of Interruption to Interconnection Service. In the event the Big Savage Project receives notice that Interconnection Service, as defined in the Big Savage ISA, will be interrupted because of a condition associated with the Mason Dixon Project, and said condition may be cured in Big Savage’s reasonable judgment by operating a circuit breaker located between the Mason Dixon Project and the Shared Facilities (the “Mason Dixon Breaker”), Big Savage shall provide notice to Mason Dixon to open the Mason Dixon Breaker. If the Mason Dixon Breaker is not opened by Mason Dixon in a commercially reasonable time as determined by Big Savage in its reasonable judgment, Big Savage shall have the right to open the Mason Dixon Breaker in accordance with Good Utility Practice as defined in the Big Savage ISA. In the event the Mason Dixon Project receives notice that Interconnection Service, as defined in the Mason Dixon ISA, will be interrupted because of a condition associated with the Big Savage Project, and said condition may be cured in Mason Dixon’s reasonable judgment by operating a circuit breaker located between the Big Savage Project and the Shared Facilities (the “Big Savage Breaker”), Mason Dixon shall provide notice to Big Savage to open the Big Savage Breaker. If the Big Savage Breaker is not opened by Big Savage in a commercially reasonable time as determined by Mason Dixon in its reasonable judgment, Mason Dixon shall have the right to open the Big Savage Breaker in accordance with Good Utility Practice as defined in the Mason Dixon ISA. Each Party shall release the other Party, its officers, directors, shareholders, members and affiliates, from any and all damages, losses, claims, including claims and actions relating to injury to or death of any person or damage to property, demand, suits, recoveries, costs and expenses, court costs, and attorney fees, arising out of or resulting from its performance or the exercise of its rights under this Section. 2.5 No Joint and Several Liability between Big Savage and Mason Dixon. The Parties acknowledge that this Agreement does not subject Big Savage to joint and several liability for any actions taken by Mason Dixon, and conversely does not subject Mason Dixon to joint and several liability for any actions taken by Big Savage. 2.6 Assignment or Transfer of Rights. Except as set forth in Section 10.6 hereof and except for an assignment or transfer to PJM, Big Savage and Mason Dixon, respectively, shall not assign or transfer any rights granted to such Party hereunder with regard to the Big Savage ISA, the Mason Dixon ISA, the Shared Facilities, or grant any permission, license, right of way or similar right with regard to the Big Savage ISA, the Mason Dixon ISA, or the Shared Facilities, without the prior written consent of the other Party, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned, denied or delayed. 2.7 Interference. Subject to the terms of this Agreement, in no event shall any Party be entitled to exercise its rights to access and utilize the Shared Facilities if the exercise of such rights would materially interfere with or limit the reasonable and necessary access and utilization of the Shared Facilities by the other Party. 2.8 Prior Written Consent. Except as set forth in this Agreement, neither Party shall take any action that results in the forbearance, foreclosure, termination or alteration of the other Party’s rights or increases the obligations or responsibilities of the other Party with regard to access to, utilization of or reliance upon the Shared Facilities without the prior written consent of the other Party, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned, delayed or denied. 4. MAINTENANCE OF SHARED FACILITIES 3.1 Operating and Capital Expenses. (i) All capital, engineering, development and other costs associated with the interconnection of the Mason Dixon Project to the Shared Facilities and the integration of the Mason Dixon Project into the operation of the Shared Facilities shall be borne by Mason Dixon alone, and to the extent Big Savage incurs any such costs, Mason Dixon shall reimburse Big Savage for the same within 30 days of receipt of invoices for such costs from Big Savage. (ii) Big Savage shall act as the Manager of the Shared Facilities and shall be responsible for the operation, inspection, maintenance, repair, alteration, relocation, improvement and replacement of the Shared Facilities and the insuring thereof. All costs and expenses incurred in the ordinary course of business in operating, maintaining and repairing the Shared Facilities, including those associated with preventative, scheduled and unscheduled maintenance, are hereinafter referred to as “Operating Expenses”. All costs and expenses incurred in upgrading, replacing, altering, relocating, or increasing the value or extending the useful life of, the Shared Facilities, or which are otherwise deemed capital expenditures under GAAP relative to the Shared Facilities, are hereinafter referred to as “Capital Expenses”. (iii) For purposes of this Agreement: · “Big Savage’s Percentage” shall, at the time used under this Agreement, mean (i) the then aggregate nameplate capacity of the Big Savage Project, divided by (ii) the then combined aggregate nameplate capacity of the Big Savage Project and the Mason Dixon Project. · “Mason Dixon’s Percentage” shall, at the time used under this Agreement, mean (i) the then aggregate nameplate capacity of the Mason Dixon Project, divided by (ii) the then combined aggregate nameplate capacity of the Big Savage Project and the Mason Dixon Project. 3.2 Allocation of Costs (i) No later than October 31 of each calendar year during the Term, commencing after the Commercial Operation Date, Big Savage shall deliver to Mason Dixon a proposed written budget for Operating Expenses for the following calendar year (“Shared Facilities O&M Budget”), describing the scheduled work to be completed in the following calendar year and the general operational plans for the Shared Facilities during such year. The draft budget shall include, at a minimum and when applicable, the billing rates, estimated cost, based on time and materials, and all fees and reimbursable costs contemplated in this Agreement, for anticipated operation and maintenance services and repairs to be provided or contracted by Big Savage during each month of the following year. When approved (or deemed approved) pursuant to subparagraph (ii) below, the Shared Facilities O&M Budget shall be the “Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget” for such year. (ii) Mason Dixon shall have thirty (30) days from receipt of a proposed Shared Facilities O&M Budget to provide comments on, approve or disapprove the same. A failure to disapprove a proposed Shared Facilities O&M Budget within such thirty (30) day period shall constitute Mason Dixon’s approval of such Shared Facilities O&M Budget (and such Shared Facilities O&M Budget will be the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget for the following year). If the Shared Facilities O&M Budget is approved by Mason Dixon, the Shared Facilities O&M Budget will be the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget for the following year. In the event that a proposed Shared Facilities O&M Budget is not approved prior to December 31 of the year prior to the year the budget relates, the Shared Facilities O&M Budget prepared and approved for the previous year shall be utilized until such time as the new Shared Facilities O&M Budget is approved (it being acknowledged that the budget for the calendar year in which the Commercial Operation Date occurs will be established and agreed upon prior to Mason Dixon securing all permanent financing on the project. (iii) If, during any calendar year, Big Savage believes that a variance is reasonably likely to occur between the actual expense of operating and maintaining the Shared Facilities and the budgeted Operating Expenses as provided in the then applicable Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget, Big Savage shall timely notify Mason Dixon of such belief in writing and advise Mason Dixon of the necessary revisions to the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget and the reasons for those revisions. If Mason Dixon (acting reasonably) agrees, the Parties shall proceed in good faith to revise the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget in such manner for the balance of the year. (iv) Big Savage shall be entitled to perform and any all work and incur all commercially reasonable and necessary costs and expenses without any further approval from Mason Dixon that (i) do not cause the overall Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget to be exceeded, and (ii) are otherwise incurred in accordance with the most recently Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget. (v) For each calendar year (or portion thereof) during the Term (A) Big Savage will bear that portion of the Operating Expenses for such calendar year (or portion thereof) which is equal to the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget for such calendar year (or portion thereof), multiplied by (ii) Big Savage’s Percentage, and (B) Mason Dixon will bear that portion of the Operating Expenses for such calendar year (or portion thereof) which is equal to the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget for such calendar year (or portion thereof), multiplied by (ii) Mason Dixon’s Percentage; all as shown in the illustrative example contained in Exhibit B hereto. Any Operating Expenses incurred in any calendar year (or portion thereof) in excess of the applicable Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget (as the same may be adjusted to the preceding clause (iii)) shall be borne by Big Savage alone. Mason Dixon shall pay to Big Savage its specified allocation of the Approved Shared Facilities O&M Budget within 30 days of receipt of any invoice from Big Savage. (vi) For each calendar year (or portion thereof) during the Term, commencing after the Commercial Operation Date (A) Big Savage will bear that portion of the Capital Expenses for such calendar year (or portion thereof) which is equal to the Capital Expenses so incurred during such calendar year (or portion thereof), multiplied by (ii) Big Savage’s Percentage, and (B) Mason Dixon will bear that portion of the Capital Expenses for such calendar year (or portion thereof) which is equal to the Capital Expenses so incurred during such calendar year (or portion thereof), multiplied by (ii) Mason Dixon’s Percentage. Mason Dixon shall pay to Big Savage its specified allocation of Capital Expenses within 30 days of receipt of any invoice from Big Savage. (vii) Big Savage and Mason Dixon shall each be responsible for procuring and paying for the station power service of their respective Projects. 3.3 Change in Ownership. Except for any sale of the Shared Facilities by Big Savage to any purchaser to whom Big Savage may freely assign or transfer this Agreement under Section 10.6, no change in ownership of the Shared Facilities shall take place during the Term without the express written consent of the Parties and the Financing Parties in both Projects. 5. CHANGE IN LAW 4.1 Change in Law. In the event that a change in the laws or regulations applicable to the Big Savage ISA, Mason Dixon ISA, the Shared Facilities, the Projects or this Agreement requires the amendment, modification or replacement of this Agreement in order to satisfy any applicable federal, state or local regulatory requirements, the Parties agree to use good faith efforts to negotiate and implement mutually agreeable terms to accomplish such amendment, modification or replacement. 6. CERTAIN COVENANTS 5.1 Authority and Operational Abilities. Each Party represents, as of the Effective Date, and covenants for the Term hereof, that such Party has the legal authority and operational abilities to fulfill its obligations under this Agreement. 5.2 Agreement to Cooperate. Each Party agrees to reasonably cooperate with the other Party so that, subject to the terms of this Agreement, each Project benefits from the full utilization and enjoyment of the Shared Facilities as are necessary for the safe and efficient operation of each such Project, compliance with Applicable Laws and regulatory requirements, and the terms and conditions of the Big Savage ISA and the Mason Dixon ISA. 5.3 Adverse Events. (i) If an operational issue arises at the Big Savage Project or Mason Dixon Project that is reasonably expected to result in a material breach by Big Savage of the Big Savage ISA or this Agreement (an “Adverse Event”), Big Savage shall, after such reasonable advance notice to the Parties hereunder as is practical under the circumstances, curtail the operations of the Project that is causing the Adverse Event. In the event of such curtailment, energy deliveries to the Point of Interconnection (as defined in the Big Savage ISA) from the Project that has caused the Adverse Event shall be limited as necessary until the Adverse Event has been cured in the reasonable judgment of Big Savage. (ii) If, as a direct result of an Adverse Event caused by the Big Savage Project or the Mason Dixon Project, Big Savage incurs costs, expenses, or penalties of any kind (“AE Costs”), Big Savage or Mason Dixon, as applicable, shall be solely responsible for such AE Costs. In the event that both Projects are responsible for the Adverse Event, and to the extent that Big Savage, in its sole and reasonable discretion, can accurately allocate responsibility for such Adverse Event between the Projects, Big Savage shall be responsible for only its allocable portion of such applicable AE Costs (and Big Savage shall allocate the remaining AE Costs to Mason Dixon). If, however, it is not reasonably possible for Big Savage, as determined in its sole and reasonable discretion, to accurately allocate such responsibility, Big Savage shall be liable for such costs in an amount equal to Big Savage’s Percentage multiplied by such AE Costs (and the remaining AE Costs shall be the responsibility of Mason Dixon). 5.4 Priority of Curtailment. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary in this Agreement, in the event of curtailment pursuant to the Big Savage ISA or the Mason Dixon ISA (or pursuant to applicable operating guides or applicable reliability standards and requirements), Big Savage shall curtail the Big Savage and Mason Dixon Projects as follows: (i) first, and if necessary in full, any Project (if any) the operation of which is contributing to a PJM system Emergency Condition (as defined in the Big Savage ISA or Mason Dixon ISA (as applicable), any applicable PJM agreements or Open Access Transmission Tariff); and (ii) thereafter, both Projects, at the same time and to an extent for each Project equal to such Project’s pro rata portion (based on such Project’s nameplate capacity) of the energy delivered to the Point of Interconnection as of the time immediately prior to the event giving rise to the curtailment. 7. MATERIAL BREACH; LIMITATIONS 6.1 Material Breach by any Party. In the event of any material breach of this Agreement by any Party and such Party fails to cure promptly such breach within a reasonable time, not to exceed thirty (30) days after receipt of written notice from the non-defaulting Party describing such breach, the non-defaulting Party shall have the right, but not the obligation, in addition to all remedies available to it at law or in equity, to: (a) cure the breach on behalf of the defaulting Party, or (b) suspend the breaching Party’s access to all or any portion of the Shared Facilities owned by such non-breaching Party for so long as such default shall be continuing and remain uncured. Notwithstanding the foregoing, in the event that a breach of this Agreement could give rise to a breach by Big Savage pursuant to the terms of the Big Savage ISA, the non-defaulting Party shall not be required to provide the defaulting Party with notice and/or an opportunity to cure in order to exercise the remedies specified in clause (a) or (b) above; provided, that the remedy specified in clause (a) may be exercised, without prejudice to any right or remedy of any Party hereunder, by any Financing Party of such Party. If a Party (or any Financing Party thereof) chooses to cure a Party’s default, the defaulting Party shall reimburse the non-defaulting Party (or such Party’s Financing Party) upon demand for all commercially reasonable costs incurred by the non-defaulting Party (or such Party’s Financing Party) in curing such default. 6.2 Liability. Except for indemnification obligations related to third-party claims for bodily injury or property damage as provided for in Section 10.7, in no event shall any Party be liable under any provision of this Agreement for any losses, damages, costs or expenses for any special, indirect, incidental, consequential, or punitive damages including, but not limited to, loss of profit or revenue, loss of the use of equipment, cost of capital, cost of temporary equipment or services, whether based in whole or in part in contract, in tort, including negligence, strict liability, or any other theory of liability. 6.3 Mason Dixon Purchase Option. If at any time during the Term, Big Savage permanently ceases the production of electric energy from the Big Savage Project, Mason Dixon shall have the option to purchase all or any portions of the Shared Facilities subject to the provisions of any applicable loan documents and agreements in favor of Big Savage’s Financing Parties and this Section (“Purchase Option”). 6.3.1 Purchase Price. The purchase price for exercising the Purchase Option shall be the Fair Market Value of the Shared Facilities (the “Purchase Price”). 6.3.2 Fair Market Value. The Fair Market Value of the Shared Facilities for purposes of exercising the Purchase Option shall be determined within thirty (30) days of Mason Dixon’s written notice to Big Savage advising of Mason Dixon’s possible interest in exercising the Purchase Option. Mason Dixon shall select, subject to Big Savage’s consent, a nationally recognized Independent Appraiser with significant national experience, qualifications and expertise in the wind industry to determine the Fair Market Value of the Shared Facilities. The Independent Appraiser shall act reasonably and in good faith to determine the Fair Market Value and shall set forth its determination of value in a written opinion delivered to Mason Dixon and Big Savage containing at least the following: (i) A discussion and description of the methodology or valuation approach used to determine Fair Market Value and the reasons that the Independent Appraiser selected the particular methodology or valuation approach for this transaction as opposed to other available methodologies or valuation approaches; (ii) A list of the property, fixtures and assets considered in determining the Fair Market Value; (iii) A discussion of the current book value of the various assets comprising the Shared Facilities; (iv) A discussion of reasonably contemporaneous valuations of other projects/assets that were considered in the Fair Market Value determination of the Shared Facilities; and (v) An evaluation and quantification of all debt and other financing obligations previously incurred by Big Savage in connection with the Shared Facilities. The valuation made by the Independent Appraiser shall be binding on Mason Dixon and Big Savage in the absence of fraud or manifest error. The costs of the appraisal shall be borne solely by Mason Dixon. If the Parties cannot agree upon an Independent Appraiser, they shall request the American Arbitration Association to select an appraiser. The fees, if any, of the American Arbitration Association, shall be shared equally by the Parties. After the Fair Market Value has been determined by the Independent Appraiser and the written opinion provided to the Parties, Mason Dixon shall have thirty (30) days to advise Big Savage whether it intends to purchase the Shared Facilities, subject to the terms hereof and the provisions of applicable loan documents in favor of Big Savage’s Financing Parties. 6.3.3 Exercise of Purchase Option. Mason Dixon may exercise the Purchase Option by tendering a notice to Big Savage that Mason Dixon has accepted the Fair Market Value determined by the Independent Appraiser and wishes to so exercise the Purchase Option. 6.3.4 Terms of Purchase. On the ninetieth (90th) day after Mason Dixon’s exercise of the Purchase Option as provided in Section 7.3.3 (the “Transfer Date”): (a) Big Savage shall surrender and transfer to Mason Dixon all of Big Savage’s right, title, and interest in and to the Shared Facilities, which shall be fully operational; (b) Mason Dixon shall receive the Shared Facilities free and clear of any liens and encumbrances; (c) the remaining period on all third party warranties for the Shared Facilities shall be transferred to the Mason Dixon; (d) Mason Dixon shall pay the Purchase Price to Big Savage by bank draft or wire transfer and shall assume all liabilities arising from or related to the Shared Facilities from and after the Transfer Date; and (f) both Parties shall (i) execute and deliver a bill of sale and assignment of contract rights containing such representations, warranties, covenants and other terms and conditions as are usual and customary for a sale of assets similar to the Shared Facilities, together with such other conveyance and transaction documents as are reasonably required to fully transfer and vest title to the Shared Facilities in Mason Dixon, and (ii) deliver ancillary documents, including releases, rights to leasehold, resolutions, certificates, third person consents and approvals and such similar documents as may be reasonably necessary to complete the sale of the Shared Facilities to Mason Dixon. 8. FORCE MAJEURE 7.1 Force Majeure. In the event of an act of God, government order or restraint, war (declared or undeclared) or warlike conditions, act of terrorism, blockade, revolution, strike, lockout, civil commotion, fire, flood, storm, epidemic or any other occurrence beyond a Party’s reasonable control (each a “Force Majeure Event”), such Party shall promptly notify each other Party thereof and, so long as such condition shall persist, such Party shall not be liable for the delay in performance of, or the failure to perform, its obligations (other than obligations for payment of amounts due hereunder) under this Agreement caused directly or indirectly thereby. The claiming Party shall give the other Party and the other Party’s Financing Party (if known) notice describing the particulars of the Force Majeure Event. Within fifteen (15) days after giving notice of the Force Majeure Event, the claiming Party shall give each other Party an estimate of the Force Majeure Event’s expected duration and probable impact. The claiming Party shall continue to furnish each other Party with timely regular reports during the continuation of the Force Majeure Event. Each Party shall promptly exercise commercially reasonable efforts to mitigate or limit the impact to its obligations hereunder as a result of the Force Majeure Event. 9. DISPUTE RESOLUTION 8.1 Disputes. In the event a dispute arises between the Parties in connection with this Agreement, the aggrieved Party shall promptly notify the other Party of the dispute in writing. If the Parties shall have failed to resolve the dispute within fifteen (15) days after delivery of such written notice, each Party shall, have the right to pursue the resolution of such dispute in accordance with the provisions of Section 9.2. 8.2 Dispute Resolution. 8.2.1 Meet and Confer. In the event of any dispute or disagreement between the Parties, the executives of each such Party shall meet to attempt to resolve the dispute or disagreement. If such executives are unable to resolve the dispute or disagreement after fifteen (15) days, the matter shall be submitted to binding arbitration in accordance with the provisions below. 8.2.2 Agreement to Arbitrate Disputes. Any controversy, claim or dispute between or among the Parties arising out of or related to this Agreement or the breach thereof that cannot be settled amicably by the Parties shall be submitted for arbitration by a single arbitrator in accordance with the provisions contained herein and in accordance with the Commercial Arbitration Rules of the American Arbitration Association (“Rules”). Judgment upon the award rendered by the arbitrator may be entered in any court having jurisdiction. The arbitrator shall determine all questions of fact and law relating to any controversy, claim, or dispute hereunder, including but not limited to whether or not any such controversy, claim, or dispute hereunder is subject to the arbitration provisions contained herein. 8.2.3 Commencement of Proceedings. Any Party desiring arbitration (the “Demanding Party”) shall serve on the other Party and its Financing Parties, and the Office of the American Arbitration Association in the State of New York, in accordance with the Rules, its demand for arbitration (“Demand”), accompanied by the name of the person chosen by the Demanding Party to select an arbitrator. The other Party shall choose a second person to select an arbitrator, and the two persons so chosen shall select the arbitrator. If the other Party upon whom the Demand is served fails to choose a person to select an arbitrator and advise the Demanding Party of its selection within fifteen (15) days after receipt of the Demand, the person chosen by the Demanding Party shall select the arbitrator. If the two persons chosen by the Parties cannot agree upon an arbitrator within ten (10) days after the designation of the second person, the arbitrator shall be selected in accordance with the Rules. All Financing Parties shall have the right to participate in any arbitration proceedings. The arbitration proceedings provided hereunder are hereby declared to be self-executing, and it shall not be necessary to petition a court to compel arbitration. 8.2.4 Location. All arbitration proceedings shall be held in the State of New York. 8.2.5 Filing Deadlines. Notice of the Demand shall be filed in writing with the other Party to this Agreement and with the American Arbitration Association. The Demand shall be made within a reasonable time after the claim, dispute or other matter in question has arisen, and in no event shall it be made after the date when institution of legal or equitable proceedings based on such claim, dispute or other matter in question would be barred by the applicable statutes of limitations. 10. MISCELLANEOUS 9.1 Relationship of Parties. By entering into this Agreement, the Parties do not intend to create hereby any joint venture, partnership, association or any other entity for the conduct of any business. Except as provided in Sections 3.4 and 7.1, nothing herein shall be deemed to authorize any Party to act on behalf of any other Party. 9.2 Non-Interference. Each Party agrees not to interfere with the reasonable and necessary utilization of the Shared Facilities by any other Party as permitted hereunder. 9.3 Modification and Amendment. The terms of this Agreement may only be modified or amended in a writing signed by all of the Parties. 9.4 Waiver. The failure of a Party to insist upon or enforce strict performance of any of the provisions of this Agreement or to exercise any rights or remedies under this Agreement shall not be construed as a waiver or relinquishment to any extent of such Party’s right to assert or rely upon any such provisions, rights, and remedies in that or any other instance; rather, the same shall be and remain in full force and effect. 9.5 Enforceability. Any provision of this Agreement that is prohibited or unenforceable in any jurisdiction shall, as to such jurisdiction, be ineffective only to the extent of such prohibition, but shall be effective to the extent of such remaining provisions hereof. 9.6 Assignment. Either Party may assign any of its benefits, rights or obligations hereunder to any third party without the prior written consent of the other Party in connection with (i) the sale of its respective Project or (ii) a collateral assignment of this Agreement to any Financing Party in connection with a financing or a refinancing of its respective Project. In all other cases, neither Party may assign any of its benefits, rights or obligations hereunder to any third party without the prior written consent of the other Party, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned, delayed or denied. 9.7 Indemnification. Each Party shall indemnify, defend and hold each other Party, its officers, directors, shareholders, members and affiliates, harmless from any and all third party damages, losses, claims, demands or suits relating to injury to or death of any person or damage to property, including court costs and reasonable attorneys’ fees, arising out of or resulting from the indemnifying Party’s negligence or willful misconduct in connection with its performance under this Agreement, except in cases of gross negligence or intentional wrongdoing by the indemnified Party. 9.8 Choice of Law, Jurisdiction and Waiver of Jury Trial. (i) This Agreement and the rights and obligations of the Parties hereunder will be governed pursuant to, and enforced, construed and interpreted in accordance with, the laws of the State of New York without regard to principles of conflicts of laws (other than Section 5-1401 of the General Obligations Law of the State of New York). Venue for resolution of any disputes under this Agreement shall be New York County, New York. (ii) Each of the Parties irrevocably and unconditionally submits to the exclusive jurisdiction of the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York for the purposes of any suit, action or other proceeding arising out of or relating to this Agreement, the transactions contemplated hereby, any provision hereof or the breach, performance, enforcement or validity or invalidity of this Agreement or any provision hereof (and agrees not to commence any suit, action or proceeding relating thereto except in such courts). (iii) THE PARTIES HERETO EACH HEREBY KNOWINGLY, VOLUNTARILY AND INTENTIONALLY WAIVE THE RIGHT EACH MAY HAVE TO A TRIAL BY JURY WITH RESPECT TO ANY PROCEEDINGS BASED HEREON, OR ARISING OUT OF, UNDER OR IN CONNECTION WITH THIS AGREEMENT, OR ANY COURSE OF CONDUCT, COURSE OF DEALING, STATEMENTS (WHETHER ORAL OR WRITTEN) OR ACTIONS OF EITHER PARTY TO THIS AGREEMENT. THIS PROVISION IS A MATERIAL INDUCEMENT FOR THE PARTIES TO ENTER INTO THIS AGREEMENT. 9.9 Inspection of Records. Each Party shall have access to any records concerning the operation and maintenance of the Shared Facilities held by any other Party upon reasonable notice and at reasonable times. 9.10 Entire Agreement. This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement of the Parties with respect to the subject matter hereof and all other agreements or understandings between the Parties regarding the subject matter of this Agreement are superseded and deemed to be null and void. 9.11 Section Headings. The section headings in this Agreement are for convenience of reference only and shall not modify, define, expand, or limit any of the terms or provisions hereof. 9.12 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in one or more counterparts, each of which when so executed shall be deemed an original, and all of which when taken together shall constitute one and the same instrument. 9.13 Specific Performance. The Parties hereto may demand specific performance of this Agreement. Each Party hereby irrevocably waives any defense based on the adequacy of a remedy at law and any other defense which might be asserted to bar the remedy of specific performance. 9.14 Notices. Any notice required or authorized to be given hereunder or any other communications between the Parties shall be in writing (unless otherwise provided) and shall be served personally or by reputable express courier service or by facsimile addressed to the relevant Party at the address stated below or at any other address notified by that Party to the other as its address for service. Any notice so given personally shall be deemed to have been served on delivery, any notice so given by express courier service shall be deemed to have been served two working days after the same shall have been delivered to the relevant courier, and any notice so given by facsimile shall be deemed to have been served on dispatch. As proof of such service it shall be sufficient to produce a receipt showing personal service, the receipt of a reputable courier company showing the correct address of the addressee or an activity report of the sender’s facsimile machine showing the correct facsimile number of the Party on whom notice is served and the correct number of pages transmitted and the date of dispatch. The Parties’ addresses for service are as follows, although each Party may change its address for service by written notice to the other Party given as provided in this Section: Big Savage: 4749 Glencoe Road, Meyersdale, PA 15552, c/o Erik Widner, Site Manager Mason Dixon: 4749 Glencoe Road, Meyersdale, PA 15552, c/o Site Manager 9.15 Amendment. This Agreement may only be amended, modified and changed by an instrument in writing signed by all of the Parties. 9.16 Construction. The language in all parts of this Agreement shall be in all cases construed simply according to its fair meaning and not strictly for or against any of the Parties hereto. 9.17 Additional Documents; Cooperation. Each Party, upon the request of the other Party, agrees to perform any further acts and execute and deliver any documents which may be reasonably necessary to carry out the provisions of this Agreement, including but not limited to, providing acknowledgement before a Notary Public of any signature heretofore or hereafter made by a Party. In addition, each Party shall fully support and cooperate with each other in the conduct of their respective obligations hereunder. The Parties acknowledge and agree that the performance of this Agreement may require them to execute additional agreements from time to time including, without limitation, a metering agreement to specify and/or confirm the ownership and operation of revenue meters and billing related thereto. To the extent necessary, the Parties shall in good faith seek and obtain all approvals or consents from third parties necessary to implement any additional agreements. 9.18 Time. Time is of the essence with respect to this Agreement. 9.19 Attorneys’ Fees. If any Party brings any action or proceeding or initiates arbitration for the enforcement, protection or establishment of any right or remedy under this Agreement, or for the interpretation of this Agreement, the prevailing party shall be entitled to recover from the non-prevailing party its reasonable costs and expenses, including actual reasonable attorneys’ fees and expenses, in connection with such action or proceeding. 9.20 Cooperation – Shared Facilities’ Operation. Each Party hereby agrees to cooperate with the other Party in the use, improvement, operation and administration of the Shared Facilities, and to act in good faith with respect to such other Party and with due consideration to the operation of each Party’s Project. 9.21 No Third-Party Beneficiary. Except for those provisions hereof which are for the benefit of Financing Parties (which Financing Parties and their respective successors and assigns are hereby expressly made third party beneficiaries hereof to the extent of their respective rights hereunder), the Parties do not intend to confer any benefit hereunder on any person, firm or corporation other than the Parties hereto. 9.22 Replacement Agreement. In the event that this Agreement is rejected or otherwise terminated as a result of any bankruptcy or insolvency proceeding regarding Big Savage, the Parties agree, to the extent permitted by existing law, to enter into a new agreement having terms substantially similar to this Agreement.
